shared_text:
Cherokee Nation is with Quannah Howe Owens.
August 6 at 10:22 PM ·

Attention: The Cherokee Nation is extending its deadline for its Respond, Recover, Rebuild Education Initiative, to give more parents time to apply!

The deadline has been extended from Aug. 7 to now Friday, Aug. 14.

Parents who have not submitted an application for a technology or clothing stipend still have time. Cherokee Nation citizens who still need to register their child for Cherokee Nation citizenship, or have a pending application for citizenship on file, can also still apply by the new Aug. 14 deadline. Citizenship applications must be completed with supporting records in order to be considered “pending.”

Click on Cherokee.org and go to the blue RRR Education Initiative icon to apply.

Programs available for education COVID-19 relief include:

A $150 to students across Cherokee Nation without regard to income or type of schooling they receive for clothes and a winter coat. For income, eligible students it’s a $300 clothing stipend.

A $400 education technology stipend is also offered for any Cherokee student ages 5 to 18 regardless of income and regardless of where they live.

The COVID-19 pandemic has hit schools and students hard in lots of ways. The very nature of education, and how it is safely delivered in the midst of the biggest public health crisis in generations, has changed dramatically. Distance learning has taken on even greater importance. The Cherokee Nation is pleased to invest $40 million in its Respond, Recover and Rebuild Education Initiative to help students and schools stay on track as we continue to deal with COVID-19.

A drop box will be placed in the Cherokee Nation complex atrium for parents and the public to drop off citizenship applications.

The Registration Department will be closed to the public starting Monday and through August 14 so that the department can focus on processing applications.

Funding for those who applied by the original deadline will be distributed soon.

Wado, to the more than 40,000 applications turned in thus far. We thank you, and are proud of the response and success from the Respond, Recover, Rebuild Education Initiative. We know our children will get off to a great school year while continuing to maintain safety.

post_text:
Cherokee Nation’s Respond Recover and Rebuild Education Initiative portal is now live at this link: https://zfrmz.com/ZQH1i5uKRo6sd2oQgsiM

Eligible citizens can access the portal to apply for these benefits:

Application Deadline: August 7, 2020 before 11:59pm CST (The previously announced school clothing assistance program has been extended. Paper applications already submitted will be processed).

Eligibility Requirements

Each child may only be reported by one applicant and must be the custodial parent or guardian of the child.

Educational Assistance Program

Citizenship: Must be Cherokee citizens on or before July 13, 2020
Residency: NO residency requirement
Age: Children between ages of five (5) and eighteen (18) years of age on or between the dates of July 1, 2020 and December 30, 2020.
Enrollment: Students concurrently enrolled in high school and college will only be eligible for the Higher Education Scholarship Technology Grant. Any applications for this program will be removed from consideration of this program.

School Clothes Program

Citizenship: Must be Cherokee citizens on or before July 13, 2020
Residency: Must live within the Cherokee Nation jurisdiction.
Age: Children between ages of five (5) and eighteen (18) years of age on or between the dates of July 1, 2020 and December 30, 2020.
Existing Applications: Any students previously submitted for the School Clothing Voucher Program will be not receive additional funding from this program. Students that have previously submitted will be processed under those guidelines established by Cherokee Nation Human Services.

If you have any questions regarding eligibility or submission please call 918-453-5000 to be directed to Cherokee Nation staff assisting with questions.

post_text: Zion School was recently blessed to receive a grant from the Tom J. and Edna M. Carson Foundation for the purchase of new Apple Macbooks and iPads. Our students and teachers will benefit tremendously from this generous grant, says Superintendent Corey Bunch. With this grant and funds received from Cherokee Nation’s Car Tag revenue we will be able to place a device into the hands of every student at Zion School from Pre-K through 8th grade. Having access to technology and learning how to use it properly is essential in today’s world. It is always our goal to prepare our students for their current and future academic needs and these devices are a major step forward for us. Bunch also says it couldn’t have came at a better time. With the challenges of school closures as a result of pandemic, we will be fully prepared moving forward if we need to conduct more distance learning in the fall. Thank you again to the Tom J. and Edna M. Carson Foundation, you are truly helping kids succeed!

post_text:
Dear Parents: Today Oklahoma's State School Board voted to keep all public schools closed for the remainder of the year for in person teaching and all extra curricular activities. Zion School is working on a distance learning plan for students to be able to complete the remainder of the year. We expect to have that plan in place and ready to implement by April 6th or sooner if possible. The Zion School school board, administration, faculty and staff remain very committed to each of our students and will do our very best to address their needs moving forward.

Thank you,

Corey Bunch
Superintendent

Dear Parent:
As you may be aware, our school district has experienced a death of a faculty member. It is with great sadness that I must inform you that we have lost a member of our school family. Ms. Stephanie Murray passed away Saturday, February 15, 2020. School will be cancelled on Wednesday, February 19th, in order for staff members & students to attend her funeral, which is to be held at Impact Church in Westville, Ok. at 1:00p.m.
We know you will join us in our concern and sympathy for the family.
Sincerely,
Corey Bunch
